
[1]rivet

   RIV'ET, v.t. [Heb. to drive.]

   1. To fasten with a rivet or with rivets; as, to rivet two pieces of
   iron.

   2. To clinch; as, to rivet a pin or bolt.

   3. To fasten firmly; to make firm, strong or immovable; as, to rivet
   friendship or affection.

    RIV'ET, n. a pin of iron or other metal with a head, driven through a
    piece of timber or metal, and the point bent or spread and beat down
   fast, to prevent its being drawn out; or a pin or bolt clinched at both
                                    ends.
